Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco—On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a potential third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a lengthy meeting on February 4—the day that marked the beginning of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two leaders released a meticulously drafted document of 5,000 words announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document was more powerful than any treaty and certainly required detailed negotiations in advance.
I am stunned that Xi seems to have fully entrusted Putin to invade and launch the war in Ukraine.
He believes that confirming himself as the lifelong ruler of China this year is merely a formality, and he is certainly confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set out to realize his lifelong dream in an incredible brutal manner.
At nearly 70 years old, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it is either now or never.
But his view of the role Russia plays in the world is distorted.
It seems he believes that the Russian people need an emperor they can blindly follow.
This system is the exact opposite of a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the Russian people, who are emotional to the point of being sentimental.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they would share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
Initially, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and then actively participated in activities promoting the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and then in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I established a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly before the Tiananmen Square massacre broke out).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have been closely watching his rise and fully understand his ruthless nature.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB officer, but he seems to have changed recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed idea.
Undoubtedly, he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He thought that Ukrainian speakers of Russian would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but in fact, they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Facing what seemed to be an overwhelming possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredible act of resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians had been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
Because Kiev was the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it is Putin who is misled.
He should have known the facts much more clearly.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The events of 2014 made him very angry.
However, when ordered to attack his Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The entrenched corruption in the Ministry of Defense when awarding contracts also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But instead of blaming himself, Putin seems to have gone mad.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions appear to be completely unchecked.
He has thrown the entire Russian army into battle and ignored all rules of engagement, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals have been attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) has also been damaged.
Up to 400,000 people in besieged Mariupol have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is very likely to lose this war.
The United States and the European Union are both sending defensive weapons to Ukraine, while trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening European resolve and solidarity.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8th, after China's Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping activities.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint in the war.
Whether Putin will yield to Xi's wishes remains fundamentally uncertain.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be ousted before they destroy our civilization.
